abstract: The members of the Grand Army of the Republic residing in Brooklyn organized a procession at the City Hall about 1 P.M. and proceeded to Green-Wood to decorate the graves in the soldiers' lot. The procession proceeded from Joralomon street to Fulton, up Fulton street to Flatbush avenue, and through Fifth avenue to Green-Wood.

abstract: The city journals continue to discuss Lord Derby's reply to the interpellation of Earl Russell, and to speculate upon the probable object the latter had in view. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, June 18. The first business which engaged the attention of the members of the National Board of Tradent the opening of the fourth day's session this morning, was the report of the Committee on Postal Telegraph Rates. abstract: There is unquestionably at the South a strong prejudice against bestowing much education on the negro. The belief is ingrained with many of the former slaveholding class that the black is incapable of much mental progress. Then, education tends to do away with class distinctions, and the native-born Southerner has a profound horror of anything which will raise the negro toward and a social equality.

abstract: We may take this  picture of "Le Semeur" as representative of the noblest qualities of Millet's art. No one who has seen it can have missed its grandeur or its simplicity, its grace or its truth. As we gaze at the darkened figure broadly scattering the grain, we perceive at once how close and accurate has been the painter's knowledge of the facts of rustic life.

abstract: DES MOINES, Iowa, June 24.
